8. publicatae enim, &c As the sub- sequent sentences still relate to married life, it would be supposed that he is here also speaking of the adulteress, and saying that she could never hope for a second marriage, which, if rich or beautiful, she might easily contract at Rome. This seems weak after what has gone before, whence it is better per· haps to suppose that he means here to speak‚ as it were parenthetically, of the unmarried.
